Thanks also to the University
of Virginia Press, who put

00:30:07.560 --> 00:30:09.380
this anthology together.

00:30:09.380 --> 00:30:09.980
It's beautiful.

00:30:09.980 --> 00:30:12.020
The work is really great.

00:30:12.020 --> 00:30:15.700
So I'm appreciative
to them, too.

00:30:15.700 --> 00:30:20.060
I'm going to read a
few shorter poems.

00:30:20.060 --> 00:30:22.940
This is the one that appears
in the anthology.

00:30:22.940 --> 00:30:27.350
It's called "Ode to Stretch
Armstrong."

00:30:27.350 --> 00:30:31.440
"Didn't you ever fling him
across the mud room?

00:30:31.440 --> 00:30:37.640
All these rules around a body,
how far it can or cannot.

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:40.200
Stretch could land hard,
and never look,

00:30:40.200 --> 00:30:42.690
so to speak, thrown.

00:30:42.690 --> 00:30:46.010
Like a pronoun, he'd leap
rivers to attach

00:30:46.010 --> 00:30:47.810
to something else.

00:30:47.810 --> 00:30:52.750
Don't you lose him in the
heat vents by the door.

00:30:52.750 --> 00:30:57.210
Somewhere, you can bet, more
of Stretch is being made.

00:30:57.210 --> 00:31:01.300
Every moment on the assembly
line is itself assemblage.

00:31:01.300 --> 00:31:06.230
Hands gluing on the legs, or
virtually no hands at all,

00:31:06.230 --> 00:31:10.520
only the sun, which
is also a machine.

00:31:10.520 --> 00:31:15.330
Once a Boy Scout on your block
had eight gold screws inserted

00:31:15.330 --> 00:31:17.160
in his shin.

00:31:17.160 --> 00:31:21.670
Once on TV, a chopper flew
so low to the earth

00:31:21.670 --> 00:31:22.950
it missed it entirely.

00:31:28.910 --> 00:31:32.780
U-Haul and the Dream
of Arrows.

00:31:32.780 --> 00:31:36.356
A little pink lemonade in
the nick of my thumb.

00:31:36.356 --> 00:31:41.850
A little radio static ringing
in my lungs, and each lung

00:31:41.850 --> 00:31:46.340
works like a cutout, since the
body can't be everywhere,

00:31:46.340 --> 00:31:49.740
can't be all things
to all mirrors.

00:31:49.740 --> 00:31:54.160
And with my windows down, I'll
pretend this isn't a U-Haul,

00:31:54.160 --> 00:31:58.480
but a huge-ass space bot bearing
me in its gaping

00:31:58.480 --> 00:32:03.760
mouth, and the two of us could
toss around ideas for miles.

00:32:03.760 --> 00:32:08.620
We could blow by a million signs
lit up, high in the sky

00:32:08.620 --> 00:32:11.160
with arrows pointing down.

00:32:11.160 --> 00:32:15.940
And I think maybe that's what
sky is, just a whole mess of

00:32:15.940 --> 00:32:18.220
incredibly sharp ends.

00:32:18.220 --> 00:32:21.720
And the U-Haul has something
he needs to say.

00:32:21.720 --> 00:32:29.630
He nearly breaks down
from not saying it."

00:32:29.630 --> 00:32:30.880
I decided to read
this next poem.

00:32:30.880 --> 00:32:35.220
It felt sort of topical with
the Super Bowl coming up.

00:32:35.220 --> 00:32:37.070
I read sort of this horrifying
statistic--

00:32:37.070 --> 00:32:40.870
America consumes more than a
billion chicken wings on the

00:32:40.870 --> 00:32:45.095
day of the Super Bowl,
more than a billion.

00:32:45.095 --> 00:32:46.840
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:32:46.840 --> 00:32:47.280
BEN PURKERT: Yeah.

00:32:47.280 --> 00:32:50.970
That's sort of staggering.

00:32:50.970 --> 00:32:56.260
The title of this poem, "Very
Nearly A Billion Wings."

00:32:56.260 --> 00:33:01.450
"This Rose Bowl, America will
polish off nearly a billion

00:33:01.450 --> 00:33:03.830
wings alone.

00:33:03.830 --> 00:33:08.400
Let's start looking at each wing
as one half of a couple

00:33:08.400 --> 00:33:10.260
in a movie theater.

00:33:10.260 --> 00:33:15.250
Or instead, a dent in the gross
figure of what we can

00:33:15.250 --> 00:33:18.140
count on one hand.

00:33:18.140 --> 00:33:24.570
A bird less its wings has a span
around five seconds left.

00:33:24.570 --> 00:33:27.620
Then, the big game unravels.

00:33:27.620 --> 00:33:30.400
One fumble too many.

00:33:30.400 --> 00:33:35.440
Loudly, a fan on his barstool
might snap, why are they

00:33:35.440 --> 00:33:37.510
cutting to the mascot?

00:33:37.510 --> 00:33:47.290
How hard is it to film
the damn field?"

00:33:47.290 --> 00:33:48.540
Just three more poems.

00:33:50.890 --> 00:33:53.695
So I work in advertising,
branding.

00:33:53.695 --> 00:33:55.490
I freelance for a few
different agencies.

00:33:55.490 --> 00:34:00.970
So a lot of my work involves
themes relative to

00:34:00.970 --> 00:34:05.420
consumerism, and how we sort
of process ads, and the

00:34:05.420 --> 00:34:06.690
relationship to the mind.

00:34:06.690 --> 00:34:08.739
So this is a poem
that sort of is

00:34:08.739 --> 00:34:11.620
interested in that territory.

00:34:11.620 --> 00:34:15.364
"Shown an image of an M&amp;M
wrapper, a subject salivates.

00:34:17.969 --> 00:34:21.230
The mind is so easily had.

00:34:21.230 --> 00:34:26.310
It's easily the first picked off
deer from a herd, the one

00:34:26.310 --> 00:34:31.480
the herd guest would go first,
but never said anything.

00:34:31.480 --> 00:34:34.070
And they let the mind
be ravaged.

00:34:34.070 --> 00:34:37.350
This way, they might
stand a chance.

00:34:37.350 --> 00:34:42.040
And it was so freeing to look
on with no mind, the parts

00:34:42.040 --> 00:34:47.020
being eaten in sequence, the
jaws closing on the very slim

00:34:47.020 --> 00:34:49.290
bones of the mind.

00:34:49.290 --> 00:34:53.920
And when the herd left to roam,
they fell sideways,

00:34:53.920 --> 00:35:04.530
their mouths, oh so close,
in the grass."

00:35:04.530 --> 00:35:08.420
I don't know what this means,
or if this is only me.

00:35:08.420 --> 00:35:11.150
But I feel like I've been seeing
a ton of people that

00:35:11.150 --> 00:35:12.400
have butterfly tattoos.

00:35:12.400 --> 00:35:15.290
Not just recently, but just sort
of throughout the course

00:35:15.290 --> 00:35:19.710
of my life, it's been sort of
this really quiet trope.

00:35:19.710 --> 00:35:21.440
I don't know.

00:35:21.440 --> 00:35:24.950
So I was interested in that, and
then I decided, instead of

00:35:24.950 --> 00:35:30.060
a person with a tattoo of a
butterfly, what about a

00:35:30.060 --> 00:35:31.525
butterfly with a tattoo
of a person.

00:35:31.525 --> 00:35:37.020
And that sort of ballooned
into whatever this is.

00:35:37.020 --> 00:35:41.010
"Tattoo On A Butterfly
Of A Woman."

00:35:41.010 --> 00:35:44.610
"The TV's so loud I
start squinting.

00:35:44.610 --> 00:35:49.800
I start at the corner of each
eye, pinching it barely enough

00:35:49.800 --> 00:35:51.630
to ruffle a bedsheet.

00:35:51.630 --> 00:35:56.680
With visible force, the TV
booms, what's coming up next.

00:35:56.680 --> 00:35:59.570
And this is distinct
from the future.

00:35:59.570 --> 00:36:04.340
I think the future's a tough
skin we always chew.

00:36:04.340 --> 00:36:08.000
We even leave some very
light marks on it.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:12.760
Once, on a date, a butterfly
lifted her wings to me.

00:36:12.760 --> 00:36:19.100
She was revealing
some pattern."

00:36:19.100 --> 00:36:20.740
And this is the last poem.

00:36:20.740 --> 00:36:22.650
Thanks again.

00:36:22.650 --> 00:36:26.960
"Love Like A Fork And Knife."

00:36:26.960 --> 00:36:31.600
"For weeks, rain bruises the
backyard, where one tree

00:36:31.600 --> 00:36:35.600
shines as a proxy for
standing upright.

00:36:35.600 --> 00:36:40.430
But a tree can't separate twigs
from leaves, let alone

00:36:40.430 --> 00:36:43.660
clouds from passing planes.

00:36:43.660 --> 00:36:48.360
And maybe it's both male and
female, so each can't split

00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:53.430
from the other, each half rooted
in something hard.

00:36:53.430 --> 00:36:58.660
And the tree is no billboard,
but still flashes like one

00:36:58.660 --> 00:37:03.560
white hot bulb, soaking up
the electric, and says to

00:37:03.560 --> 00:37:07.860
whoever's around, there's
water where I am.

00:37:07.860 --> 00:37:10.970
Also some sun here.

00:37:10.970 --> 00:37:17.890
It's possible to say things
simply by not dying."

00:37:17.890 --> 00:37:19.140
Thank you very much.

00:37:25.060 --> 00:37:28.830
And the next and last and very
talented poet we have is

00:37:28.830 --> 00:37:30.350
Sophia Starmack.

00:37:30.350 --> 00:37:35.060
She received an MA in French
and Francophone literature

00:37:35.060 --> 00:37:38.280
from Bryn Mawr College, and is
currently completing an MFA in

00:37:38.280 --> 00:37:39.930
poetry at Sarah Lawrence.

00:37:39.930 --> 00:37:42.820
She works as a writing teacher
and tutor in New York City.

00:37:42.820 --> 00:37:44.070
Sophia.

00:37:50.385 --> 00:37:51.480
SOPHIA STARMACK:
Thanks so much.

00:37:51.480 --> 00:37:54.510
I'm really excited that I
finished that MFA since this

00:37:54.510 --> 00:37:55.285
book was published.

00:37:55.285 --> 00:37:57.570
Yeah.

00:37:57.570 --> 00:38:01.340
No, it's really important
you can finish things.

00:38:01.340 --> 00:38:02.470
Thanks so much.

00:38:02.470 --> 00:38:04.775
It's really special
to be here.

00:38:04.775 --> 00:38:08.710
The poem in the book is from a
long poem that I wrote, which

00:38:08.710 --> 00:38:12.350
is sort of a love story that I
wrote for myself, and also for

00:38:12.350 --> 00:38:15.880
the place where I grew up, which
is in Western New York--

00:38:15.880 --> 00:38:18.980
a really small village.

00:38:18.980 --> 00:38:22.860
So I'm going to start there, and
just keep going and read

00:38:22.860 --> 00:38:24.975
you a bit from that
very long poem.

00:38:28.860 --> 00:38:33.740
"If I, too, thinks Alice,
then the glacier.

00:38:33.740 --> 00:38:37.425
In the beginning, grinding its
fingers, the grit of schist

00:38:37.425 --> 00:38:41.610
and granite sticks to its lonely
bone, its white soul to

00:38:41.610 --> 00:38:43.840
steer it, a whale bone
whistling north.

00:38:43.840 --> 00:38:50.910
If the glacier, thinks Alice,
then I. If I, then the ice.

00:38:50.910 --> 00:38:54.320
If I, too, then the mouth of the
river, the mouths of the

00:38:54.320 --> 00:38:55.160
dead through my dream.

00:38:55.160 --> 00:38:59.120
If I, too, then the rock and the
names carved in the rock.

00:38:59.120 --> 00:39:04.840
If I, too, then my mother, her
fringe leather jacket.

00:39:04.840 --> 00:39:08.070
If I, too, then the calf, and
the cow's hanging udder.

00:39:08.070 --> 00:39:12.280
If I, too, then the field,
each wheat spear turning.

00:39:12.280 --> 00:39:15.670
If I, too, then the song, under

00:39:15.670 --> 00:39:17.100
the light shaft striking.

00:39:17.100 --> 00:39:20.990
If I, too, then each blade
of sun unturning, and the

00:39:20.990 --> 00:39:26.010
darkness and the darkness
hollering over the valley and

00:39:26.010 --> 00:39:29.315
after 10 millennia, even a
glacier gives up the ghost.

00:39:38.480 --> 00:39:41.990
I had forgotten they still made
places, thinks Jo, like

00:39:41.990 --> 00:39:46.850
this, when the hot sun slams
back in, her eyelids, the ripe

00:39:46.850 --> 00:39:50.125
darkness, the drugstore
softens around her.

00:39:50.125 --> 00:39:54.280
What is a drugstore after
all, remembers Jo?

00:39:54.280 --> 00:39:57.130
Something about sweet syrup
and chipped ice.

00:39:57.130 --> 00:40:01.920
Something about penny candy,
thinks Jo, asking the pimpled

00:40:01.920 --> 00:40:04.870
boy behind the counter
for a soda.

00:40:04.870 --> 00:40:09.160
The sly ceiling fan unwinding,
dust from hot September.

00:40:09.160 --> 00:40:13.100
I'll take it, she says, and
pays for a cherry Coke.

00:40:16.930 --> 00:40:20.580
Cherry Coke, please, says
Alice in her sun dress,

00:40:20.580 --> 00:40:24.440
sitting on the concrete stoop,
Alice in her feather down,

00:40:24.440 --> 00:40:26.080
furs like a blonde coat.

00:40:26.080 --> 00:40:29.890
Alice, on the edge of becoming
Alice, drinks like a greedy

00:40:29.890 --> 00:40:35.470
wolf from the waxy paper cup,
leaves sweet sweat on the rim.

00:40:40.560 --> 00:40:44.560
It's only the strap of a sun
dress in hot September, the

00:40:44.560 --> 00:40:47.790
poured cement of an old time
drugstore, the strap of a

00:40:47.790 --> 00:40:50.260
sundress, a sun-peeled
shoulder.

00:40:50.260 --> 00:40:53.470
Shouldn't you be, asks
Jo, in school?

00:40:53.470 --> 00:40:55.910
But Alice holds her eye.

00:40:55.910 --> 00:40:57.000
Says nothing.

00:40:57.000 --> 00:41:01.270
They sip at Cherry Cokes and
suck the ice, the wax, flakes

00:41:01.270 --> 00:41:04.750
on the cup, the skin peels
on the shoulder.

00:41:04.750 --> 00:41:08.070
I have become a woman, writes
Alice in her notebook, but

00:41:08.070 --> 00:41:12.260
before disappearing through the
greening light it slips,

00:41:12.260 --> 00:41:14.820
just the strap of her sun
dress, her peeled skin

00:41:14.820 --> 00:41:18.250
shoulder, and Jo, without
thinking, pulls it up.

00:41:22.530 --> 00:41:25.920
With the radio down, and the
windows at one with her

00:41:25.920 --> 00:41:29.040
thoughts, Jo's got seven
women on her mind.

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:32.600
Seven women like seven stars,
one for each finger of her

00:41:32.600 --> 00:41:36.700
left hand, and two for the
invisible fingers of feeling.

00:41:36.700 --> 00:41:39.910
One the stories she reaches
out for, two the stories

00:41:39.910 --> 00:41:41.050
reaching back.

00:41:41.050 --> 00:41:45.050
Seven women, seven stars,
seven sisters, tucked in

00:41:45.050 --> 00:41:46.900
Orion's belt.

00:41:46.900 --> 00:41:50.850
Jo knows Orion, knows his heavy
shield, buckles against

00:41:50.850 --> 00:41:55.320
the night, knows the heavy arms
of his terror, knows the

00:41:55.320 --> 00:41:57.678
little knife keeps
tucked close.

00:42:04.022 --> 00:42:05.900
Which is more illicit?

00:42:05.900 --> 00:42:10.320
A not so little girl in the
street light, or the driver,

00:42:10.320 --> 00:42:12.440
home from a guilty errand?

00:42:12.440 --> 00:42:16.680
Alice owns the street, tuned
to the night machine, a car

00:42:16.680 --> 00:42:19.640
shining approaching, holding
her ground in

00:42:19.640 --> 00:42:21.900
the one lane street.

00:42:21.900 --> 00:42:25.020
The thrill in her t-shirt,
the dew and the crickets.

00:42:25.020 --> 00:42:29.230
Alice knows summer is dying, and
Alice wants to be real in

00:42:29.230 --> 00:42:33.030
the headlight, wants to be
touched under her dress by

00:42:33.030 --> 00:42:37.240
flakes of light that beam from
the headlights, holds the

00:42:37.240 --> 00:42:40.830
unknown gaze of the stranger,
late from work,

00:42:40.830 --> 00:42:42.180
or something worse.

00:42:42.180 --> 00:42:45.200
They both know the needle
of night time.

00:42:45.200 --> 00:42:48.470
Alice spreads herself on the
darkness and bounds into the

00:42:48.470 --> 00:42:50.220
arms of the ash tree.

00:42:50.220 --> 00:42:52.490
The car slows, and
scuttles by.

00:42:52.490 --> 00:42:56.045
They have seen, not
seen, each other.

00:42:56.045 --> 00:43:02.910
For everyone knows this town
goes to bed at 9:00.

00:43:02.910 --> 00:43:08.200
Back home, the driver considers
the moon, its horns

00:43:08.200 --> 00:43:11.860
and its feathers, the orange
disc of its suffering.

00:43:11.860 --> 00:43:15.610
Down the hill he steers his
lonely station wagon.

00:43:15.610 --> 00:43:18.055
This is the weight of one.

00:43:18.055 --> 00:43:22.210
He slides his feet, his leather
clogs and hand-knit

00:43:22.210 --> 00:43:25.260
socks, his graying beard
his weakness.

00:43:25.260 --> 00:43:29.320
Slumps at the table, leaves
the light untouched.

00:43:29.320 --> 00:43:32.830
Upstairs, his wife
breathing, the

00:43:32.830 --> 00:43:34.530
children sticky with dreams.

00:43:34.530 --> 00:43:40.350
He has a taste at once of frost,
October coming, the

00:43:40.350 --> 00:43:43.510
moon dropped pebbles
of ice and trouble.

00:43:43.510 --> 00:43:46.160
The driver watched them glitter
off the skin of the

00:43:46.160 --> 00:43:49.250
girl made real in
his headlight.

00:43:49.250 --> 00:43:53.530
Hands strong and sullen,
he cradles his head.

00:43:53.530 --> 00:43:57.750
Alone in the darkness alone, in
the breathing, and winter

00:43:57.750 --> 00:43:58.770
to come."

00:43:58.770 --> 00:44:00.230
Thank you so much.

00:44:00.230 --> 00:44:01.480
Thanks to everyone.

